<font color="#FF0000">A WORLD BENEATH THE WAR</font><br>
<tt>Tue Feb 18  7:28:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Here is a documentary I saw at the Telluride IndieFest recently, which I highly recommend. For once, it's an opportunity to see the war from the point of view of the Vietnamese. <br><br>
&quot;A WORLD BENEATH THE WAR: THE SECRET TUNNELS OF VIET NAM&quot; is a 53 minute documentary by Pham Quoc Thai and Janet Gardner that reveals the untold story of Viet Nam's tunnels. It uses some rare archival footage shot by North Vietnamese filmmakers that has never been seen in the West. Life is recorded in these underground tunnels - which served not only as sleeping quarters, but they also had a hospital, schools, theater, a printing press and broadcasting equipment. With personal stories about the war, the documentary shows their struggle to survive and the price they paid for independence.<br><br>
This documentary is available through Filmakers' Library, Inc. 124 East 40 St. N.Y., N.Y. 10016.  Phone: 212-808-4980. It will be distributed by NAATA (National Asian American Telecommunications Association) in San Francisco.<br><br>
It will be screened at the San Francisco Asian American Film Festival on Tuesday, March 11, 1997 at 1:00 pm at The Kabuki Theater in San Francisco, and is also expected to be on selected PBS stations this spring. <br><br>
